          <Comment>This variant results in the deletion of part of exon 3 (c.341-7_356del) of the G6PC gene. It is expected to disrupt RNA splicing. Variants that disrupt the donor or acceptor splice site typically lead to a loss of protein function (PMID: 16199547), and loss-of-function variants in G6PC are known to be pathogenic (PMID: 8182131). This variant is not present in population databases (gnomAD no frequency). This variant has not been reported in the literature in individuals affected with G6PC-related conditions. This variant disrupts a region of the G6PC protein in which other variant(s) (p.Gly118Ser) have been determined to be pathogenic (PMID: 25308557; Invitae). This suggests that this is a clinically significant region of the protein, and that variants that disrupt it are likely to be disease-causing. For these reasons, this variant has been classified as Pathogenic.</Comment>
